<!-- JUSTICE -->
<div class="w-section" id="justice">
  <div class="w-inner">
    <div class="section-label">Data Justice</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">Who is visible. Who is not.</h2>
    <p style="color: var(--muted); max-width: 640px;">The architecture of prediction market data encodes assumptions about who matters, whose knowledge counts, and whose suffering is legible.</p>
    <div class="justice-grid">
      <div class="justice-item"><h3>Commodification of democracy</h3><p>Citizens' collective decisions — elections, referenda, policy votes — become instruments for profit extraction. The incentive structure rewards accuracy over accountability, speed over deliberation.</p></div>
      <div class="justice-item"><h3>Information asymmetry</h3><p>Private Discord servers, government leaks, and corporate insider access create structural advantages invisible in the public trade data. The playing field is not level; the data does not show this.</p></div>
      <div class="justice-item"><h3>Exclusion by design</h3><p>KYC requirements, jurisdictional restrictions, and the need for disposable capital filter who can participate. The resulting "crowd" is not a representative public — it is a financially privileged subset.</p></div>
      <div class="justice-item"><h3>Abstraction of harm</h3><p>Markets on war, deportation, and political repression reduce affected populations to binary outcomes. People become implicit categories — "migrants," "casualties," "voters" — stripped of identity and proximity to harm.</p></div>
      <div class="justice-item"><h3>Truth by market</h3><p>When media and policymakers cite prediction market probabilities as ground truth, they launder the perspectives of wealthy speculators into apparently neutral epistemic claims. Markets don't reveal truth; they reflect power.</p></div>
      <div class="justice-item"><h3>Missing voices</h3><p>Interviews with affected communities, ethnography of trader spaces, and movement archives could surface what trade logs cannot: how people experience being turned into speculative assets, and how they resist.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

